					<div class="jeg_posts jeg_block_container">
                
                <div class="jeg_posts jeg_load_more_flag">
                <article class="jeg_post jeg_pl_md_2 format-standard">
                <div class="jeg_thumb">
                    
                    <a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-soft-skills-at-sea-building-emotional-resilience/" aria-label="Read article: Soft Skills at Sea: Building emotional resilience"><div class="thumbnail-container  size-715 "><img decoding="async" width="350" height="250" src="https://safety4sea.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/shutterstock_2221662701-350x250.jpg" class=" wp-post-image" alt="emotional resilience" /></div></a>
                </div>
                <div class="jeg_postblock_content">
                    <h3 class="jeg_post_title">
                        <a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-soft-skills-at-sea-building-emotional-resilience/">Soft Skills at Sea: Building emotional resilience</a>
                    </h3>
                    <div class="jeg_post_meta"><div class="jeg_meta_author coauthor"><span class="meta_text by">by</span><a href="https://safety4sea.com/author/ap/">The Editorial Team</a></div><div class="jeg_meta_date"><a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-soft-skills-at-sea-building-emotional-resilience/"><i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i> February 27, 2026</a></div></div>
                    <div class="jeg_post_excerpt">
                        <p>Emotional resilience helps children cope with challenges such as separation, stress, anxiety, and loneliness. By understanding and applying practical strategies, parents can support their children in feeling secure, valued, and emotionally balanced—even during extended time apart.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article><article class="jeg_post jeg_pl_md_2 format-standard">
                <div class="jeg_thumb">
                    
                    <a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-addressing-crew-shortage-continuously-collect-feedback-and-take-action/" aria-label="Read article: Addressing crew shortage: Continuously collect feedback and take action"><div class="thumbnail-container  size-715 "><img decoding="async" width="350" height="250" src="https://safety4sea.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/shutterstock_2678120987-350x250.jpg" class=" wp-post-image" alt="feedback" /></div></a>
                </div>
                <div class="jeg_postblock_content">
                    <h3 class="jeg_post_title">
                        <a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-addressing-crew-shortage-continuously-collect-feedback-and-take-action/">Addressing crew shortage: Continuously collect feedback and take action</a>
                    </h3>
                    <div class="jeg_post_meta"><div class="jeg_meta_author coauthor"><span class="meta_text by">by</span><a href="https://safety4sea.com/author/ap/">The Editorial Team</a></div><div class="jeg_meta_date"><a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-addressing-crew-shortage-continuously-collect-feedback-and-take-action/"><i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i> February 27, 2026</a></div></div>
                    <div class="jeg_post_excerpt">
                        <p>Regularly collecting feedback is essential to ensuring that policies genuinely meet seafarers’ needs. GMF’s All Aboard Alliance emphasizes this in its last Sustainable Crew Guideline, highlighting the power of meaningful feedback.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article><article class="jeg_post jeg_pl_md_2 format-standard">
                <div class="jeg_thumb">
                    
                    <a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-safety-first-protecting-your-eyes-while-at-sea/" aria-label="Read article: Safety First: Protecting your eyes while at sea"><div class="thumbnail-container  size-715 "><img decoding="async" width="350" height="250" src="https://safety4sea.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/shutterstock_236934592-350x250.jpg" class=" wp-post-image" alt="protecting your eyes at sea" /></div></a>
                </div>
                <div class="jeg_postblock_content">
                    <h3 class="jeg_post_title">
                        <a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-safety-first-protecting-your-eyes-while-at-sea/">Safety First: Protecting your eyes while at sea</a>
                    </h3>
                    <div class="jeg_post_meta"><div class="jeg_meta_author coauthor"><span class="meta_text by">by</span><a href="https://safety4sea.com/author/ap/">The Editorial Team</a></div><div class="jeg_meta_date"><a href="https://safety4sea.com/cm-safety-first-protecting-your-eyes-while-at-sea/"><i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i> February 25, 2026</a></div></div>
                    <div class="jeg_post_excerpt">
                        <p>Eye injuries happen in a split second, but their consequences can last a lifetime. Protecting your eyes at sea requires a combination of thoughtful risk assessment, proper PPE selection, functional safety guards, and attention to comfort and usability.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>
            </div>
